message: Always cook raw ingredients with the stove first; they usually become 20-value 'cooked' items. Then, use a grain (like tortilla, rice, bread, or corn) as a base. Combining the grain with ONE cooked protein or vegetable will get you 40 value. Combining the grain with TWO *different* cooked proteins/vegetables will get you 80 value. Be careful! Adding a third cooked item to an already complex grain-based dish (making it a grain + 3 cooked items) almost always results in an 'overcomplicated' item with 0 value. Submit your score once you hit 80 with two cooked ingredients on a grain base to be safe!

message: The 'stove' tool is very useful. Always cook raw proteins (like beef, bacon, beans) and raw vegetables (like mushrooms, tomatoes, potatoes, cucumbers) with the stove first; they will gain value (usually 20). Combining a cooked protein with a grain (like cooked beef and tortilla, or cooked bacon and wheat) usually gets you to 40 value. The sweet spot for high scores (often 80) is adding one cooked vegetable to that combination (e.g., cooked beef taco + cooked mushroom). Be careful: adding too many ingredients to an already complex item, especially a fourth ingredient, often makes it 'overcomplicated' and drops its value to 0. The 'water' tool can be used on rice, but it requires the stove afterward for value. Aim for a cooked protein + grain + cooked vegetable for your highest score and submit when you reach 80 to avoid overcomplicating it.
